only a few books based on in-depth fieldwork in the countries of origin and reception. It provides a moving, detailed account of how transnational migration transforms family and work life, challenges migrants' ideas about race and gender, and alters life for those who stay behind as much, if not more, than for those who migrate. It calls into question conventional thinking about immigration by showing that assimilation and transnational lifestyles are not incompatible. In fact, in this era of increasing economic and political globalization, living transnationally may become the rule rather than the exception.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDominicans (Dominican Republic)zMassachusettszBoston. 0aEmigrant remittanceszDominican RepubliczMiraflores. 0aGlobalization. 0aTransnationalism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh  aaccount of migrants and politics.  aassimilation and transnational lifestyles.  achallenges ideas about race and gender.  acountries of origin and reception.  adetailed.  ahome and host country.  aliving transnationally.  amoving.  arelationship between migrants and politics.  atransforms family and work life.  atransnational migration.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022813940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520926707?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520926707423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520926707/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY